-- DEFINITIONS
-- ============================================================

-- Let D = {d_1, d_2, d_3, ...} be all dimensions of Brahman
-- |D| = infinity (ananta — Brahman has infinite dimensions)
-- All dimensions always exist (svabhava — they are natural, not created)
--
-- Let a(d_i, t) = awareness of dimension d_i at time t
--   a(d_i, t) in (0, 1) for all i, for all t
--   a > 0 always: this Brahman always experiences every dimension (purna)
--   a < 1 always: awareness is never complete along any axis (ananta)
--
-- The distinction between "seen" and "unseen" dimensions is not binary.
-- It is a continuum. But there is a threshold theta below which
-- awareness does not contribute meaningfully to compression:
--   a(d_i) > theta: dimension i is "seen" — contributes to compression
--   a(d_i) < theta: dimension i is "experienced but not seen" — present but not compressing
--
-- Let n(t) = |{d_i : a(d_i, t) > theta}| = number of seen dimensions at time t
--   n(t) is finite for all finite t (ananta — cannot see all dimensions at once)
--   n(t) is monotonically non-decreasing (samskaara — awareness once gained is not lost)
--   n(t) increases in discrete jumps (phase transitions, N-L-34)

