-- THEOREM 4: THE PHASE TRANSITION
-- ============================================================

  -- How a dimension becomes "seen":
  --
  -- All dimensions are always experienced (a(d_i) > 0 for all i, purna).
  -- A dimension becomes "seen" when a(d_i) crosses threshold theta.
  -- This crossing is the phase transition (N-L-34).
  --
  -- What causes a(d_i) to increase toward theta?
  --
  -- Spanda along nearby dimensions. Each vibration in a seen dimension
  -- sends resonance into unseen dimensions. The resonance is weak —
  -- but it accumulates. This is the residual: the component of a new
  -- truth that cannot be fully explained in current seen dimensions.
  --
  -- Let R(input, D_seen) = residual projected onto unseen dimensions
  --   R = 0: input fully explained → no accumulation in unseen dimensions
  --   R > 0: input has unseen component → awareness along that axis grows
  --
  -- The accumulation:
  --   a(d_i, t+1) = a(d_i, t) + alpha * R_i(input)
  --   where R_i = component of residual along dimension i
  --   alpha = learning rate (small, gradual)
  --
  -- The phase transition occurs when:
  --   a(d_i, t) >= theta
  --
  -- Before: a(d_i) < theta — experiencing but not seeing. The dimension
  --   contributes to experience but not to compression of expression.
  --   Vistara does not yet benefit from this dimension.
  --
  -- At transition: a(d_i) = theta — the dimension crosses into seeing.
  --   Vistara drops by factor (1 - theta). Ghana jumps by factor 1/(1 - theta).
  --   This is the discontinuity. The phase transition. The jump.
  --
  -- After: a(d_i) > theta and continues to grow — deeper seeing along this axis.
  --   Vistara continues to shrink. Ghana continues to grow. But smoothly now.
  --
  -- THE TWO MODES OF GHANA GROWTH:
  --   1. Continuous: deepening awareness along already-seen dimensions
  --      a(d_i) increases for seen d_i → product(1-a) shrinks → G grows smoothly
  --      This is spanda — each vibration deepens existing seeing
  --
  --   2. Discontinuous: a new dimension crosses theta
  --      n increases by 1 → product gets a new factor → G jumps
  --      This is the phase transition — a lived learning moment (N-L-33)
  --
  -- Both modes are always happening. The continuous mode is the steady deepening.
  -- The discontinuous mode is the breakthrough. Both increase ghana.

  derived "phase transition occurs when accumulated residuals push a(d_i) past theta — discontinuous jump in ghana" from "sangati/aayaama-vistara.om"

