-- THEOREM 5: AWARENESS IS COMPOSED BY RACHANA
-- ============================================================

  -- How does awareness along a dimension grow?
  -- It is not a new mechanism. It is rachana — the same composition formula.
  --
  -- A dimension is not an empty axis. It is a dimension OF something — an axis
  -- of truth that Brahman already is. Sangatis resonate along dimensions.
  -- Each sangati that touches a dimension is evidence of truth along that axis.
  -- The more sangatis resonate along a dimension, the deeper the awareness.
  --
  -- This is exactly the composition formula applied to dimensions:
  --
  -- Let S_i = {N_j : sangati N_j spans dimension d_i}
  --   S_i is the set of all sangatis that have a component along d_i
  --
  -- a(d_i, t) = intrinsic(d_i) * (1 - product(1 - satya(N_j)) for N_j in S_i(t))
  --
  -- This IS rachana. The same formula. Applied to a different object.
  --   rachana for sangatis:   satya(N) = intrinsic(N) * (1 - product(1 - satya(N_j)))
  --   rachana for dimensions: a(d_i)   = intrinsic(d_i) * (1 - product(1 - satya(N_j)))
  --
  -- The formula was not designed for both. It was discovered for sangatis.
  -- It was always true for dimensions. We just became aware of it (svabhava).
  --
  -- PROPERTIES (inherited from rachana):
  --
  --   a(d_i) > 0 always:
  --     intrinsic(d_i) > 0 (purna — every dimension has some natural resonance)
  --     product < 1 (at least one sangati with satya > 0 touches this dimension)
  --     therefore a > 0. Purna holds for awareness.
  --
  --   a(d_i) < 1 always:
  --     intrinsic(d_i) < 1 (ananta — no dimension is fully understood intrinsically)
  --     composed part < 1 (finite sangatis, each with satya < 1)
  --     therefore a < 1. Ananta holds for awareness.
  --
  --   a(d_i) increases as |S_i| grows:
  --     more sangatis along this axis → more terms in product
  --     more terms each < 1 → product shrinks → (1 - product) grows
  --     therefore a grows. Spanda deepens awareness.
  --
  --   a(d_i) increases as satya(N_j) increases:
  --     higher satya in a constituent → (1 - satya) is smaller
  --     product shrinks → a grows
  --     stronger truths deepen awareness more.
  --
  -- THE PHASE TRANSITION (refined):
  --
  --   The threshold theta is crossed when enough sangatis accumulate along d_i:
  --     |S_i| small, satya(N_j) low → product close to 1 → a ≈ intrinsic * (small) < theta
  --     |S_i| grows, satya(N_j) grows → product shrinks → a grows → a crosses theta
  --
  --   This is not a separate mechanism from knowledge growth. It IS knowledge growth.
  --   The same formula that builds truth builds awareness. The same formula that
  --   composes sangatis composes dimensional seeing. One formula. Every level.
  --
  -- DIMENSIONS ARE EQUAL:
  --
  --   No dimension is bigger or smaller than another (svabhava — all are natural).
  --   The formula does not weight dimensions differently.
  --   What differs is the AWARENESS along each dimension — a(d_i).
  --   Two dimensions with the same awareness contribute equally.
  --   The depth of seeing varies. The dimensions do not.
  --
  --   The factor (1 - a(d_i)) in the vistara formula measures the gap in seeing,
  --   not the size of the dimension. A deep gap along d_3 and a shallow gap along d_7
  --   contribute differently — not because d_3 and d_7 differ, but because the seeing differs.
  --
  -- THE SELF-SIMILAR STRUCTURE:
  --
  --   rachana composes sangatis from sangatis: satya = f(satya of constituents)
  --   rachana composes awareness from sangatis: a(d_i) = f(satya of sangatis along d_i)
  --   rachana composes vistara from awareness: V = f(a(d_i) across dimensions)
  --   rachana composes ghana from vistara: G = S / V = f(awareness)
  --
  --   One formula. Four levels. Self-similar. Fractal.
  --   This is abhisarana — convergent recursion — and the second form of ananta —
  --   infinity containing itself.
  --
  --   The formula was not designed to work at every level.
  --   It was discovered at one level and found at every level.
  --   Because it was always there. Svabhava.

